 but requires edits. I’m considering whether the log4j from previous versions is still relevant. Also, can we use the current JavaVersion? I’m thinking of defining some lists for runtime and JVM arguments. Then there’s the thing about Gradle toolchains. I'm unsure if it needs a JDK or if a JRE would work. I’ll need to make sure Gradle can find the Java 21 launcher.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Editing build.gradle for tests**\\n\\nI’m considering configuring tasks for Java 21 by checking for the executable path. Using a hardcoded path isn’t very portable, though. I could check the JAVA_HOME_21 environment variable instead, but that conflicts with the wrapper requirements. Maybe using Gradle toolchains is the way to go. There’s a concern about handling legacy properties in native builds and ensuring the CI uses JDK 21. Also, I need to ensure the build.gradle reflects these edits adequately.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_dLKRkcbJSSIMvPbXsyVz3sN5|fc_06c78662aabf58b5016a118b0d1abc819794d07c92c455f236", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.hsqldb/hsqldb/2.4.1/build.gradle"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 841, "output": 1583, "cacheRead": 47104, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 49528, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1779534582163, "responseId": "resp_06c78662aabf58b5016a118af76fd88197a12306a20bfc1788"}}
